    "contents": "# Document the new workflow\n\nThe new workflow renders cleanly. Write a short, agent-facing skill file so that\nfuture agents (and the human) know it exists and how to run it. You have file\ntools — write the file, then report its path.\n\n## Workflow\n\n- Name: {props.workflowName}\n\n## Design\n\n{JSON.stringify(props.design, null, 2)}\n\n## Write the skill\n\nCreate `{props.skillsDir}/{props.workflowName}.md` (create the directory if\nneeded). Use YAML frontmatter then a concise body:\n\n```\n---\nname: {props.workflowName}\ndescription: <one line — what it does and when to reach for it>\nworkflow: {props.workflowName}\n---\n```\n\nThe body must tell an agent:\n\n1. What the workflow does and when to use it (1–2 sentences).\n2. Its inputs — especially `prompt` and any typed knobs from the design.\n3. How to start it:\n   `bunx smithers-orchestrator workflow run {props.workflowName} --prompt \"…\"`\n   (or `--input '{…}'` for structured inputs).\n4. How to run it detached and watch it: `-d` to detach, then\n   `smithers ps`, `smithers logs <runId> -f`, `smithers inspect <runId>`.\n5. How to handle blocked states: `smithers approve <runId>` for approval gates,\n   `smithers why <runId>` for signal waits, `smithers cancel <runId>` to stop.\n\nKeep it practical and short — no marketing copy. Match the style of any existing\nfiles in `{props.skillsDir}` and update rather than duplicate if one already\ncovers this workflow.\n\n## Output\n\nReturn a one-line `summary` and the `skillPath` you wrote.\n\nREQUIRED OUTPUT:\n{props.schema}\n"
